<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-3025-26> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#material> "Indian handmade paper, red and black inks, watercolour, white paint. \r\nThe handmade paper has flaws, protruding fibres, impurities, back particles and micro-holes, all resulting from the manufacturing process.\r\n\r\nRecto: the primary outline was executed with red ink, then the secondary outline was done with a greyish ink and the final outline was drawn with black ink. A white primer was applied on the background to prepare the support for colour application. Krishnaâ€™s dupatta was lightly coloured in yellow. The borders feature a few cursory sketches, in the upper edge a flower and in the bottom edge, the profiles of two women and a man. \r\nVerso: a folding chair was drawn but the perspective of its legs was not accurate so the painter attempted to conceal it with a white wash. There is also a human profile and two flowers with four petals drawn in blue ink as well as a series of brush lines and paint stains.\r\nLots of paint stains are visible on the recto and the verso.\r\nModern label at verso with title and description in Dutch of the image\r\nFor more details see attached pdf conservation report." .
